{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01WijNyKji6az1waCvXg7XN9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me summarize the pattern and plan the implementation:\n\n**TrustManager pattern (what we're mirroring):**\n1. `readTrustedCABundle()` reads the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap from the operator namespace\n2. `computeCABundleHash()` computes SHA-256 of the PEM data\n3. The hash is returned from `createOrApplyDefaultCAPackageConfigMap()` \n4. The hash is passed to `createOrApplyDeployment()` → `getDeploymentObject()` → `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume()`\n5. `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume()` stamps the hash into the deployment's pod template annotations\n6. The `deploymentModified()` function detects drift by comparing the annotations between desired and existing deployments\n\nFor IstioCSR, the controller already has the CA ConfigMap creation and ConfigMap watching logic in place. I need to add the hash computation and annotation stamping to trigger pod restarts when the CA certificate changes. compute the hash and pass it to the deployment creation. I also need to update the deployment modification check to compare pod template annotations, and add a watch on the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap so the controller reconciles whenever it changes.\n\nLooking at this more carefully, the controller needs to track the CNO-injected CA bundle separately from other CA sources and trigger rolling restarts by updating the pod template annotation whenever the bundle content changes. I need to create a new file for reading and hashing the CA bundle, add a constant for the annotation key, and modify the deployment functions to accept and apply the CA content hash to the pod template spec.\n\nIn the main reconciliation function, I'll read the CA bundle and compute its hash before passing it to the deployment creation, and I need to update the comparison logic to check if the pod template annotations have changed. I should also add a watch on the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap so the controller reacts when it updates.\n\nWait, let me think about this differently—\n\nthe IstioCSR controller is namespace-scoped, not cluster-wide like TrustManager, so I can't just reuse the same watch pattern. The CNO-injected ConfigMap doesn't have the labels that the existing map function expects, so I'll need a separate watch handler that knows how to map that ConfigMap back to the relevant IstioCSR instances. TrustManager uses a predicate to identify the CNO-injected ConfigMap by namespace and name, then applies a mapFunc that returns a fixed singleton. For IstioCSR, I need a separate mapFunc since the label-based extraction won't work for the CNO ConfigMap. The cleanest solution is adding a dedicated watch for the CNO ConfigMap with its own mapFunc that lists all IstioCSR resources and enqueues them.\n\nBut actually, since there's only one IstioCSR instance enforced by the controller, I could simplify this by just reading the CNO ConfigMap during reconciliation instead of watching it directly—the existing ConfigMap watches would already trigger when needed.\n\nFor the CNO ConfigMap watch itself, I need to map those changes back to IstioCSR reconcile requests. The challenge is that IstioCSR is namespace-scoped and could live in any namespace, so I can't just use a fixed name like TrustManager does. I'd need to either list all IstioCSR instances in the map function or find another way to discover which namespace it's in.\n\nWriting the map function... match, the deployment won't be updated unnecessarily. I need to add the annotation comparison to the `deploymentSpecModified` check so it properly detects when the CA bundle hash changes and triggers a reconciliation.\n\nThere's an important distinction here though—the CNO-injected CA bundle is separate from the CA data IstioCSR manages internally. The goal is specifically to watch for changes to that cluster-wide trusted CA bundle and restart the IstioCSR pods when it updates, likely so they can pick up new trusted CAs for proxy communication.\n\nI need to handle the case where the CNO CA bundle ConfigMap might not exist yet, since it's injected by CNO and won't be present in all environments. The implementation should gracefully skip the hash annotation if the ConfigMap is missing, only computing and stamping the hash when it actually exists. I need to handle the \"not found\" case gracefully when IstioCSR tries to read the CNO CA bundle, since it doesn't control whether that ConfigMap exists like TrustManager does. Now I'm laying out the implementation plan: creating a new file to read and hash the CA bundle, adding a hash annotation constant, modifying the deployments handler to stamp the hash on pod templates, updating the install logic to read the bundle and pass the hash through, and adjusting utilities as needed. Writing the ConfigMap helper functions... Writing Go functions... Modifying the deployment functions to accept and apply the CA content hash annotation, which gets stamped onto the pod template to trigger rolling restarts when the CA bundle changes. Reading the CA bundle and computing its hash to pass along with the deployment creation, then I need to update the deployment spec comparison logic to also check if annotations have changed so that the rolling restart annotation triggers properly. I see that `maps.Equal` is already available in the utils, so I should use that for consistency with how `deploymentModified` checks annotations. Since the istiocsr utils don't currently set annotations on the pod template, the fetched deployment would have nil annotations initially. When there's a CA bundle, the desired state gets the annotation while fetched doesn't, triggering an update on the first reconciliation. This is the right behavior, so I'll add the same `maps.Equal` check to `deploymentSpecModified`.\n\nNow I'm setting up a watch for the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap. I need to create a predicate to identify the right ConfigMap, then build a handler that maps ConfigMap changes to IstioCSR reconciliation requests. Since I don't know the IstioCSR namespace ahead of time, the handler will list all IstioCSR instances across the cluster. Writing the watch configuration...\n\nI'm realizing that the `mapFunc` needs access to the reconciler to list IstioCSR resources, similar to how TrustManager works but with the added complexity of needing to query multiple instances rather than a singleton. Writing the map function... The mapFunc is a closure that runs at reconcile time, not setup time, so accessing the cache through `r.List` is fine. I can see `r.List` is already used in `utils.go` in the `disallowMultipleIstioCSRInstances` function, so the `CtrlClient` definitely supports it. Now I need to think through the complete implementation and how to handle different error cases when reading the trusted CA bundle during reconciliation.\n\nI'm planning to add the CA bundle reading logic after validation and labels but before the deployment step, computing a hash of the bundle content if it exists, then passing that hash to the deployment creation function.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether errors from reading the CA bundle should be fatal here. Unlike TrustManager where it's required, the CNO CA bundle might not exist in all IstioCSR environments. I've already handled the case where the ConfigMap doesn't exist by returning an empty string without error, but if the ConfigMap exists and is missing the key, that should probably surface as an error since the CNO-injected ConfigMap should have the expected content.\n\nActually, there might be a brief window where the ConfigMap exists but hasn't been populated yet. I should adjust the logic to treat a missing or empty key as a warning rather than an error—log it and return empty without failing, matching the behavior when the ConfigMap doesn't exist at all.\n\nWriting error handling logic... I'm mapping out the error handling logic: ConfigMap not found returns nil gracefully, a missing key is treated as an error, and a present key gets hashed and returned. Now I need to update the function signature and all its callers—both in the main code and the test file—to pass the new `caContentHash` parameter through the call chain.\n\nI'm reconsidering the design approach: instead of threading the hash through function parameters like TrustManager does, I could read the CA bundle directly inside `getDeploymentObject` to keep changes more localized.\n\nActually, threading the hash through parameters is cleaner because it separates concerns—the reconcile flow reads the CNO CA bundle and computes the hash, then passes it to the deployment function which just stamps it. Let me go with that approach and write out the final implementation, starting with checking how many test cases need updating in `deployments_test.go`.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3196,"cache_read_input_tokens":77180,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3196,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ee2b31ea-64c4-4fa9-a3d1-0a7236e5eed0","uuid":"0cb023b2-dc92-44a0-bb73-0ed5a54f95a6","timestamp":"2026-07-20T14:49:31.864Z","request_id":"req_vrtx_011CdDVVkEHpsYYgs6Js6PKR"}
